    <body>
        <div xml:id="NA398-kiḷavi">
            <p type="edition">itu muṉṉuṟa uṇarttu (ET: /; C1: uṇarntu) pakaṟkuṟi vantu mīḷun talaimakaṉ “nī tāṉ ivaḷatu taṉmai āṟṟuvi” eṉac (ET: tōḻi) colliyatu.</p>
            <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how HE who returned after coming to the day tryst, having informed(?) before: “You yourself will appease her nature.”</p>
            </div>
      <div xml:id="NA398">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            urukeḻu teyvamuṅ karantuṟai yiṉṟē</l>
<l>            virikatir ñāyiṟuṅ kuṭakkuvāṅ kummē</l>
<l>            nīralaik kalaiiya kūḻai vaṭiyāc</l>
<l>            cāa yavvayi ṟalaippa vuṭaṉiyain</l>
<l>            tōrai makaḷiru mūrey tiṉarē</l>
<l>            paṉmalar naṟumpoḻil paḻicci yāmuṉ</l>
<l>            ceṉmō cēyiḻai yeṉṟaṉa mataṉetir</l>
<l>            collāṇ melliyal cilavē nallakat</l>
<l>            tiyāṇa riḷamulai naṉaiya</l>
<l>            māṇeḻiṉ maḻaikkaṇ ṭeṇpaṉi koḷavē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            Fearful gods won’t remain hidden</l>
<l>            and the sun with broad beams bends itself to the west</l>
<l>            and the women have reached the village, [after] the game</l>
<l rend="indent">                they had enjoyed together(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="term">uṭaṉ iyaintu ōrai makaḷir</term>: here we have a construction problem. To be expected is either a different word order (<term xml:lang="term">ōrai</term> is not related at all to the rest of the sentence): <term xml:lang="term">ōrai uṭaṉ iyaintu</term>, or at the very least a <term xml:lang="term">peyareccam</term>: <term xml:lang="term">uṭaṉ iyainta ōrai</term>. Otherwise we could try a different connection, that is <term xml:lang="term">orai</term> simply as attribute to <term xml:lang="term">makaḷir</term> ("women in play"), while <term xml:lang="term">uṭaṉ iyaintu</term> would go with the rest of the line: "enjoying together to slap [each other’s] pretty bellies." The gesture as such is mentioned elsewhere, as in a formulaic parallel in NA 179.3 .</note> , while they slap [their] pretty bellies</l>
<l rend="indent">                 exhaustedly, [their] hair, disarrayed from being dashed by the water,</l>
<l rend="indent">                not trickling [anymore].</l>
<l>            Adoring the grove fragrant with many blossoms we said:</l>
<l>            “we in front, up, [o you with] red jewels!”</l>
<l rend="indent4">                Upon that</l>
<l>            [she of] soft nature didn’t say [even] a few [words],</l>
<l rend="indent">                while the flourishing young breasts on [her] good chest became wet,</l>
<l rend="indent">                while [her] rain eyes of glorious grace took clear dew.</l>
            </lg>
      </div>
